The Multi-Modal Shift: Augmenting AI with Rich Data

Andrew Dyer

Mar 11, 2025   15 min read

Key Insights

  • Multi-modal data significantly enhances AI capabilities by aligning text, image, audio, and video inputs.
  • Large-scale datasets like InternVid and OpenHumanVid have notably improved AI model realism and accuracy.
  • Collecting and curating massive multi-modal datasets remains challenging due to scale, cost, and ethical concerns.
  • Grass leverages decentralized infrastructure, enabling efficient and extensive harvesting of multi-modal web data.
  • Recent upgrades to the Grass network have substantially increased its capacity, reinforcing its role in future AI training.

Introduction

Multi-modal data refers to information spanning multiple senses or modalitiessuch as text combined with images, audio, or video. Multi-modal learning enables AI systems like LLMs to gain richer, more nuanced understandings by aligning information across multiple vectors.

In recent years, there's been significant momentum toward integrating diverse modalities into foundational models. By late 2024, multi-modal capabilities shifted from innovative to nearly standard, with major companies launching models that "see and hear." Examples include OpenAIs GPT-4 accepting image inputs, Anthropics Claude 3.7 Sonnet, Googles Gemini 2.0, and Alibabas Qwen-2 VLall embracing image, audio, or even video data. Google's Gemini 1.5 Pro notably pioneered video inputs alongside images and audio, underscoring the growing importance of video in AI interfaces.

This shift toward multi-modal training is driven by its expansion of an AI model's capabilities. For example, models trained on synchronized video and text can reason effectively about visual events over time, a task challenging for text-only systems. Audio adds context like tone, speaker identity, and environmental sounds, boosting comprehension and grounding. Recent studies highlight that incorporating audio significantly strengthens a model's understanding of events depicted in video.

Each modality brings distinct strengths: images convey spatial detail, text supports abstract reasoning, audio provides temporal cues and emotional context, and video captures motion dynamics. Training models simultaneously across these modalities results in more robust, contextually aware AI systems. As applications grow in fields such as robotics, autonomous vehicles, and immersive virtual assistants, multi-modal interpretation becomes essential.

But expanding large-scale training to include these varied data types is challenging, requiring both novel model architectures and extensive, well-aligned training datasets. This report explores how the AI community is addressing these challenges, focusing on recent developments. We will cover both new multi-modal datasets and the emergence of infrastructure like the Grass networka protocol aimed at crowdsourcing and leveraging web-based multi-modal data for AI development.

Developments in Large Datasets for Training

Training cutting-edge multi-modal models requires unprecedented volumes of data. Breakthroughs in computer vision and image-language models are still driven by dataset scale for example, the 2022 LAION-5B dataset of 5.8 billion image-text pairs enabled independent researchers to train and replicate large vision-language models like CLIP and Stable Diffusion. Now, with video and audio entering the mix, the research community has turned to assembling comparably large datasets for these richer modalities. Google DeepMinds Gemini 1.5 paper detailed multiple reasons why augmenting LLMs with multiple modalities (or incorporating them from scratch) is desirable:

  • Better domain transfer: Because the model sees concepts in multiple forms, it can generalize more effectively to new tasks or domains where only partial information is present.
  • Cross-modal connections: The model benefits from learning shared patterns across modalities. This synergy can improve capabilities in tasks like visual question answering, captioning, describing complex scenes, or retrieving precise timestamps based on text prompts.
  • New emergent capabilities: Models can handle tasks that blend different input types. They also tend to produce more nuanced or context-aware responses.
  • Continued performance gains: Whereas purely text-based models may hit diminishing returns at a certain dataset scale, multi-modal models often show an extended phase of improvement. This indicates that richer data sources keep feeding the model with novel perspectives.

Several efforts in the past few years produced new large-scale, open-source video and audio datasets intended to boost model performance:

InternVid

InternVid is a video-text dataset that represents a leap in scale for video understanding. Described in a paper by Wang et al., InternVid contains over 7 million Youtube videos, totaling nearly 760,000 hours of footage, which were sliced into 234 million short clips paired with detailed textual descriptions. To put this in perspective, InternVids clip and word count are orders of magnitude larger than previous video-caption datasets like HowTo100M or WebVid. The authors employed an LLM to automatically produce captions using transcripts, Youtube metadata, and other context, reducing the need for human-labeling.

Training multi-modal models on InternVid has already shown clear benefits: the creators trained a model called ViCLIP on this data, and it achieved state-of-the-art (SOTA) zero-shot action recognition and video retrieval performance. Massive, diverse video datasets can yield more powerful and transferable video-text representations, boosting capabilities like finding relevant video clips from text queries. Moreover, InternVids scale allowed the researchers to explore video dialogues and generative tasks (like text-to-video generation) by producing interleaved video-text training sequences, pointing toward future video-centric AI assistants.

The challenge with InternVid, however, came in collecting and curating it. Even with automated captioning, assembling millions of video clips required scraping public web videos and ensuring the captions were accurate and descriptive. This raises issues of data quality, copyright, and diversity that have to be managed. Nonetheless, InternVid stands as a milestone, showing that web-scale video data can be harvested for training foundation models.

OpenHumanVid

While InternVid focused on broad video content, OpenHumanVid tackles a subset: high-quality human-centric videos with rich annotations. Human motion and activities are especially important (for applications like realistic video generation, sports analysis, etc.), yet previous datasets lacked in quality and detail. OpenHumanVid contains a carefully curated collection of videos featuring people performing a wide variety of actions, with detailed textual captions describing both the persons appearance and their motions. The dataset even adds modality tracks like skeleton pose sequences and corresponding speech audio. By including multimodal context (video + pose data + audio + text), this dataset gives models multiple aligned views of human activity. While the ~105,000 hours of video is a fraction of InternVid, it is more carefully curated around human movement.

When the researchers fine-tuned video generation models on OpenHumanVid, they found they could substantially improve the realism and accuracy of generated human motions, as reflected in better evaluation metrics, without degrading performance on more general video generation tasks. Producing coherent results required aligning text descriptions with specific movements (including facial expressions and body pose). Precise multi-modal labels help the model learn more complex relationships.

The challenges here included obtaining detailed captions and annotations for videos. The authors likely had to employ human annotators or advanced pose estimation models and speech recognition to get skeletons and transcripts. Ensuring diversity (varied activities, different people, backgrounds) was also important to avoid a narrow dataset. OpenHumanVids release is highly valuable for any researchers working on video generation or human motion understanding, as it fills a quality gap in available data.

Sesame AI

Sesames conversational AI model did the rounds on X last week, as many were impressed by its fluency and humanness. While Sesame did not reveal too much about its curated dataset, we know it was trained with around one million hours of publicly available, English audio data. While this scale is smaller than some video-text datasets like InternVid, Sesames Conversational Speech Model (CSM) brings some unique efficiencies to multi-modal learning. The result is a voice that adapts seamlessly to conversational flow with very low latency. In their blog post, the authors noted that: In general, we observe that performance improves with larger models, supporting our hypothesis that scaling enhances the synthesis of more realistic speech. It seems we will be able to scale the performance of these speech models with more data and algorithmic improvements in the same way that we scaled text-only models.

VALID

Our last notable dataset revealed last December is VALID (Video-Audio Large Interleaved Dataset), developed collaboratively by Grass Protocol, LAION, and Ontocord. VALID combines approximately seven million video clips and thirty million audio snippets from YouTube videos into aligned tri-modal data points, totaling about 14 terabytes. Each snippet includes synchronized video frames, audio tracks, and detailed textual descriptions or transcripts.

The VALID dataset was curated from Creative Commons-licensed YouTube videos, using automated approaches like perceptual hashing to reduce redundancy and employing OpenAI's Whisper model to transcribe non-English audio. This method addressed some issues faced by earlier datasets like LAION-5B, which briefly had to be taken down because it merely linked to certain controversial or possibly copyright images. By restricting content sources to solely Creative Commons-licensed videos, performing proactive filtering to remove explicit content, and providing direct hosting, VALID has demonstrated a more robust approach to ethical dataset creation.

Despite ongoing curation challenges, the general trajectory is clear: larger and more diverse multi-modal datasets are emerging as key fuel for training the next generation of foundation models. Gemini 2.0 in particular was trained with even smaller video datasets than the ones mentioned here, like Kinetics 400 and HMDB51. So frontier models have a lot of room to scale in this direction. Both academia and industry will likely continue to aggressively invest in dataset creation and curation. Grass has already proven itself to be a valuable contributor and piece of infrastructure assisting in this effort.

Grass Value & Infrastructure Edge

Massive multi-modal datasets like we described above have already contributed to improved model understanding and performance. Its clear that the millions of videos on Youtube and other video-hosting sites are a treasure trove of data when curated properly. But large, open datasets are small in number and generally static. Thus another part of the model-training puzzle will be collecting and updating this data in an efficient, scalable way. This is where Grass comes into play.

Grass is a protocol and network designed to crowdsource the gathering of web data including multi-modal content by leveraging a decentralized infrastructure. In this section, we provide a primer on how Grass works and examine its recent Sion upgrade that boosts its data collection capabilities. Well also discuss how the GRASS token fits into the ecosystem.

Primer

At its core, Grass is a decentralized network of nodes that scrape and process raw data from the web, transforming it into structured datasets for AI and other uses. The twist is that these nodes are not data center servers but everyday users who share their unused internet bandwidth through the Grass application. In other words, anyone can run a Grass node (through the Desktop app, and soon a separate piece of hardware), allowing their internet connection to be used to route web requests and gather data. This concept is analogous to a crowdsourced web crawler or a residential proxy network companies data collection requests are distributed across millions of user devices globally, making the web requests appear as ordinary user traffic from various regions. This method has a couple of benefits: it bypasses the blocks and biases that data-center crawlers face (since many sites flag or throttle scraping from known servers), it localizes data collection (a node in the Netherlands can retrieve region-specific content that a US server might not see, for instance), and it can achieve a scale and frequency that non-profit scrapers like The Common Crawl cannot match.

When a company or researcher needs to scrape data, they submit the requests to the network. The requests get routed to Grass nodes (user devices) which fetch the content from the target websites as if they were the user browsing. The fetched data (whether its an HTML page, an image, a video file, etc.) is then sent back to Grasss infrastructure where it is often cleaned and reformatted into structured datasets; however, according to the Grass team, most LLM creators prefer to do the filtering and processing themselves. Grass ultimately acts as a coordinator it has validators and routers in the network that distribute tasks to nodes and ensure both reliability and data provenance. The end result is an Internet vacuum at enormous scale: with millions of people contributing, Grass can scrape huge quantities of public web data every day.

By early 2025 Grass had over 3 million active nodes worldwide, collectively scraping more than 1 petabyte of public web data per day. The scraped data ranges from text (web pages, documents) to images and especially video, which is a focus given the high demand for video data to train AI. Grass aggregates this firehose of data, applies any necessary filters, and then curates it into datasets that are made available to enterprises or research labs. Those entities might either purchase specific, filtered datasets (e.g., a collection of millions of captioned images, or transcribed videos) or use Grasss network in real-time for their own data collection needs. Because Grass operates on a decentralized model, it can potentially offer data access at lower cost than traditional data brokers or scraping services.

A few technical points underscore Grasss infrastructure edge. Grass is built as a layer-2 network on Solana, employing a zero-knowledge-proof based data ledger to ensure integrity and transparency of the collected data. Each web request and response can be logged on this ledger, creating an immutable proof of what was collected and from where. This is important for data transparency: if a model is trained on Grass-provided data, theres a verifiable record of the datas origin (addressing concerns like what went into my AI model?). Grass also prioritizes privacy and security user nodes share bandwidth but do not have their personal data exposed; the system is designed so that nodes are essentially blind conduits and any potentially sensitive data is handled server-side with strict protections.

In effect, Grass has created a platform that transforms what was once wasted bandwidth into a collective asset for AI development, while aligning incentives so that both data seekers and data providers benefit.

Sion Upgrade

The Grass network underwent a major upgrade in the past few months known as the Sion upgrade. This upgrade was rolled out in phases and significantly enhanced the scalability and throughput of the network.

Phase 1: Grass introduced improvements in scraping efficiency optimizing how data requests are batched and processed which led to a surge in activity without needing proportionally more compute (essentially a big gain in efficiency per node).

Phase 2: The goal in phase 2 was to deploy those optimizations to distribute workloads across more nodes, leading to higher sustained scraping speeds. The team added new scraping techniques for processing 4k video, images, and text which greatly improved the networks capacity.

Despite some sporadic interruptions as the protocol had to work with new cloud storage providers upon maxing their capacity, the improved efficiency of the network is evident in the amount of data scraped per day. Expanded scraping capacity will be increasingly important on the high-quality video-scraping front that will demand more throughput. According to Grass main cloud storage provider, Backblaze, Grass is now uploading some 2-3 petabytes of data per day, while customers are sending requests for tens of petabytes every month. For context, the entire Common Crawl dataset (which conducts monthly crawls around .25 petabytes each), is probably around 10 petabytes total. Grass specifically had to move to Backblaze because they do not charge fees for data deletion or egress (transferring data out of storage for customer use), indicating sizable customer demand.

Value Accrual & Risks

An interview with co-founder of Grass, Andrej Radonjic, emphasized how demand for bandwidth for live context retrieval (LCR, or updating LLM output for new information scraped from the recent web) will use GRASS to power the transaction on the network. So even if a customer pays for live data with fiat, that is ultimately converted into GRASS and used to reward stakeholders like validators and users.

But LCR is not live just yet, and it is not the only service customers will be and are currently paying for. According to Radonjic, as of now, 100% of the current revenue to the Grass foundation is being directed into further investments in the scraping infrastructure. Investors have complained about the opaqueness around total revenues and how they may eventually flow back to the GRASS token in a direct way. The team is fairly tight-lipped about the composition of their enterprise clients and the size of their deals due to confidentiality agreements, and there does not seem to be a clear timeline for when those revenues would be redirected towards token holders versus infrastructure improvements. Any future clarity around revenue and value accrual would, of course, be grounds for a significant re-rating higher for GRASS.

Looking Ahead

Grass has set up some very powerful and valuable infrastructure. In a world that has yet to make full use of the internets multi-modal data, Grass now has a firehose of potentially high-quality video, audio, and image data scraped from the public web at an unprecedented scale. Before the Sion upgrade, Radonjic noted that Grass had already scraped some 20% of Youtube in its entirety - almost three billion videos worth. That number has likely greatly expanded in the months since. If the performance difference in video generation models is even partially derived from data availability for training, then these billions of videos should be quite valuable.

The team has also teased ways for the community and potentially agents to interact with Grass data. A new Data Labeling tab has also been added to the Grass dashboard - chances are there may be another way for users to earn Grass points outside of merely contributing unused bandwidth. Users helping annotate or provide context to the daily inflow of web data could enhance an already valuable and rapidly growing asset.
